snippet.textDisplay:
I'm going to say it. Please don't shoot me down, but the NHS 111 response does not take into consideration community transmission, even if people answer yes to the symptoms questions. It's focus is wholly on those who have travelled from affected countries or have had contact with those who have recently returned from those places. We know community transmission has happened in the UK and in terms of those with 'mild symptoms', people could be forgiven for assuming their symptoms are down to the common cold or other virus, which is then legitimised by the NHS111 response.

I am concerned that there do not seem to be any reports on how people can distinguish mild COVID-19 symptoms from other viruses. I am concerned community transmission is not being addressed publically. I am worried that in light of this, community transmission is more likely to spread, due to lack of government and health agency response and public education.

snippet.textDisplay: The 4 inserts are highly similar to known sequences from the HIV surface proteins gp120 and gag, into the S surface protein of a human-infectious coronavirus. The Lancet paper published a few days ago reported that this virus is susectible to HIV anti-virals. The scientists who wrote this paper used the sequences from all known strains of corona virus to make this comparison and it can be replicated by anyone as the method used, comparing sequences with commonly used bioinformatic software, can easily be verified. IMHO, the chance that these insertions would happen by chance is slim because of the high similarity to HIV surface protein sequences in these 4 insert sequences. None of the 4 inserts are similar to sequences from 2019-nCorV or any known human-infective corona virus, but all 4 are easily matched to HIV surface protein sequences. Here is access to the full sequence --> https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nuccore/MN908947
